  "bib_entries": {
    "83597614": {
      "title": "Myxomycetes: A Handbook of Slime Molds",
      "abstract": "This book identifies all the species one is likely to encounter, with extensive information on their structural features, distribution, and ecological associations. Superbly illustrated, including keys, it is an introduction to their biology as well as a field guide."
    },
    "85391316": {
      "title": "Changes in a former chestnut-dominated forest after a half century of succession",
      "abstract": "In 1932, E. Lucy Braun surveyed a chestnut-dominated forest on Salt Pond Mountain in southwestern Virginia. The vegetation of this same site was resampled during the summers of 1982 and 1983 to determine the extent and nature of compositional changes after a half century of succession. Quercus rubra, which formed only 11 T% of the canopy in 1932, is now the dominant species, and Castanea dentata, which once made up 85% of the canopy, has disappeared from the canopy completely. Acer rubrum increased in importance, and Q alba declined. Several species (Acer saccharum, Amelanchier arborea, Betula lenta, Prunus serotina and Robinia pseudoacacia) not recorded as canopy trees in the original study are now present in the canopy. Results of the present study are compared to those from other recent investigations of the post-blight composition of upland forests in areas of the southern Appalachians where chestnut was once abundant. The general pattern that emerges is that after a half century of succession no single species has assumed the dominant or codominant role once occupied by chestnut in these communities."
    }
  }
}